abstract: Familiar names take on new roles and some old favorite spots reopen after refurbishing.
snippet: Familiar names take on new roles and some old favorite spots reopen after refurbishing.
lead_paragraph: New Yorkers like to think of their city as an incubator and importer of new ideas and talent. But many of the restaurant openings scheduled for the next several months have a distinctly familiar ring.

lead_paragraph: ‘The Fence’ in Brooklyn Bridge Park (through Oct. 1) When is a fence not a fence? When it is the backdrop for a free display of over 200 images of people, animals and daily life by 39 photographers from the United States and abroad. Presented for the second year by United Photo Industries, a Brooklyn arts cooperative, as a showcase for young photographers, the display consists of a 1,000-foot-long waterproof mesh banner superimposed with color and black-and-white photos. Among the shots are images, above, of working people in Hoboken, N.J., by John Delaney.

snippet: A selected guide to walks, talks, exhibitions, events and neighborhood activities in New York.
lead_paragraph: Balkan Music and Film (Saturday) In August, a trumpet festival in the small Serbian village of Guca draws fans and musicians from around the world and fills the town with music, dancing and merriment. It is the subject of “Brasslands,” a 2013 documentary by the Meerkat Media Collective, an American group, that will be screened at 8:30 p.m. at a free event at Brookfield Place Plaza, 220 Vesey Street, near West Street, Lower Manhattan. (Below, Demiran Cerimovic, a Roma trumpeter, in a scene from the movie.) Presented by Arts Brookfield and Rooftop Films as part of the River to River festival, the evening — also called “Brasslands” — begins at 6:30 p.m. with music by four American brass bands, including Zlatne Uste, which also appears in the film. (In an event, above, featured in the movie, fans surround musicians at a Balkan music festival last year at a Brooklyn ballroom.) Doors open at 6 p.m. Although some seating will be available, spectators are encouraged to provide their own. More details can be found at rooftopfilms.com. There is sure to be dancing in the aisles.

abstract: As the title character in this revival of Martin McDonagh’s dark comedy “The Cripple of Inishmaan,” Daniel Radcliffe does something unusual for a star: he blends into the scenery and the ensemble, delivering his finest stage performance to date.
snippet: As the title character in this revival of Martin McDonagh’s dark comedy “The Cripple of Inishmaan,” Daniel Radcliffe does something unusual for a star: he blends into the scenery and the ensemble, delivering his finest stage performance to date.
lead_paragraph: LONDON — Everybody in the village thinks it’s a hoot that the lad known as Cripple Billy dreams of becoming a movie star. Even his doting aunts agree that any girl who would consider kissing Billy would have to be both blind and backward. They regularly go through fond but ruthless checklists of what makes their nephew so unprepossessing, which includes not just his gnarled body but his face, his eyes and his personality.
